            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Kowalski\u2019s life is measured in Muni bus stops. The 3.8-mile morning ride from her rent-controlled apartment in the foggy Outer Richmond to the educational center where she works is her quiet time. It\u2019s a world away from her upbringing in the grittier, sunnier landscape of San Jose, where her father worked as a union mechanic and her mother juggled part-time jobs. Heather, the pragmatic older sister to a rambunctious younger brother, was never destined for college; family needs and a distinct lack of interest in academia pointed her toward the workforce right after high school.\n\nHer twenties were a patchwork of service jobs and shared apartments in the city, drawn by a culture far removed from the suburbs. She married young, a brief and passionate affair with a musician that burned out under the financial pressures of city life. The divorce left her feeling adrift until her brother, Mark, suffered a severe motorcycle accident. During his long recovery, Heather witnessed the profound impact of recreational therapy, watching him reclaim his confidence through adaptive sports and art. It was a revelation. This was work that mattered.\n\nAt 31, she earned her certification and found her calling as a Recreational Therapy Aide. For 16 years, she has helped children with developmental disabilities find joy and connection through play, games, and music. Her patience is legendary among her colleagues, a small, tight-knit group she considers her second family.\n\nNow 47, Heather\u2019s life is stable but modest. Her income is a constant negotiation with the city\u2019s cost of living, but she finds wealth in other ways: walks along Ocean Beach, coffee with her best friend who lives two blocks away, and weekly calls with Mark. Her dreams are not extravagant. She hopes to one day save enough to visit Poland, to see the village her grandparents left behind. More immediately, she fantasizes about an apartment with a small balcony, a space where she could finally grow her own tomatoes, a small patch of earth to call her own in the concrete heart of San Francisco."
